Well ending 2022 with COVID definitely sucks but I got to say that it’s been a fantastic year for aviation spotting and travel. I have the chance to meet some new friends around the World and spend a lot of time with some good old ones. Having the chance to travel for a living is a true blessing and took my spotting adventure to a worldwide level. Stay tuned later for a post with some of my favorite captures from 2023. Happy New Year🥂🥂
.

Here’s a recap from 2022 with some of my favorites subjects and pics. We start with the Texas Flag Viper from the 457th Fighter Squadron on NAS Fort Worth. Next 2 legacy Hornets from the River Rattlers during the New Orleans Airshow. A  French Mirage 2000D landing in Leewarden Netherlands, a Lufthwaffe CH53G, an AMX from the 51st Fighter Wing at Istrana Air Base Italy and Spanish Navy Harrier at NAS Rota Spain.
And let’s finish with Knight 1-1, F117A taxing in Savannah and a German Tornado blasting off at Nörvenich Air Base.

Phantom Phorever! I have been in Korea now for 10 days, flying around DHL cargo. On my spare time I was planning a visit at Suwon Air Base, home of the last Phantoms in the ROKAF. Unfortunately I leaned that foreigners can’t rent a car in Korea unless in possession of an IDP  aka international driving permit 😩, and since I don’t have one I am shit out of luck. Luckily looks like my flight schedule will bring me back here next month so I will try again. In the meantime I was able to take a cab to Seoul to visit to Korea War Memorial and see many former ROKAF aircrafts including this beautiful F4!
The Phantoms entered service in Korea in 1977 and now the only Squadron that flies this mighty jet is the 153th FS at Suwon AB.  The F4 will retire by the end of 2023 to leave place for the F35s and KF21.
.
.

Cloudy skies yesterday in South Korea, but I took advantage of my Incheon layover to take a drive to Suwon Air Force Base, home of the last ROKAF Phantoms!
The base hosts 3 Squadrons, the 101st and 201st equipped with KF5E/F and F5F, and the 153rd Squadron with the mighty F4E. I was really lucky to see through the day 19 Tigers and 7 Phantoms flying local missions. 2023 is the last year for both the F5s and F4s in Korea so I hope to be back at Suwon again in the summer.

Today another post from Kleine Brogel and this is a special Viper. This is aircraft FA-95, the first Belgian F16AM to reach the end of her structural life of 8000 flight hours. I was super lucky to see her first flight with this new livery on Wednesday, just around 7999 total hours.. She flew again on Friday during Spotter Day for her last time and for what I heard from the locals, she was part of the static display for the rest of the show.
It was a blessing once again to be able to witness this. Slowly the BAF will retire all the Vipers that will be replaced by the new F35A. It’s definitely bittersweet but by living in Fort Worth, I am looking forward to see “Belgium First Lightning” Test Flight at Lockheed Martin.
.
.

What an amazing way to end this Outbase in Germany with a quick trip to France with my friend @adrafphotography . Yesterday after my flight from Turkey, we decided to drive to Nancy Air Base, home of the 3rd Escrade de Chasse of the French Air Force. This huge base hosts 4 squadrons of Mirage 2000D but recently became home for  7 of the only 9 Mirage 2000B left in the French inventory. This beautiful plane was originally based at the Base Arienne 115 in Orange, South France, but after the  retirement of the C model, the two seaters were sent to Nancy.
Also something unique about this jet…the fuel tank on the belly has special color cause it’s the same one used in June 2022 by the Farewell Colored Mirage2000C during the last flight in Orange.
.
.

Swipe left!! A few shots from the gorgeous Boeing E6B Mercury working the pattern at NAS JRB Fort Worth.
The Mercury is a very unique aircraft and her job is to conveys instructions from the National Command Authority to fleet ballistic missile submarines.

The E-6B replaced Air Force EC-135Cs in the Looking Glass role, providing command and control of U.S. nuclear forces should ground-based control become inoperable.
